1. push block (runs when code is pushed)
on:
  push:
👉 on:

This tells GitHub:

“Here are the events that should trigger this workflow.”

👉 push:

This means:

Run the pipeline whenever someone pushes code to the repository.

So this is your deployment trigger for direct code changes.

📌 Branch filter under push
    branches:
      - main
      - qa
      - dev
👉 branches:

This restricts which branches can trigger the workflow.

Line-by-line meaning:

main → triggers pipeline when code is pushed to production branch
qa → triggers pipeline for QA/testing environment
dev → triggers pipeline for development environment

👉 So:

Push to dev → run dev pipeline
Push to qa → run QA pipeline
Push to main → run production deployment

📌 Path filter under push
    paths:
      - 'backend/**'
      - 'frontend/**'
      - '.github/workflows/deploy-app.yml'
👉 paths:

This means:

Only run the workflow if specific files/folders change

Line-by-line meaning:

'backend/**'
→ triggers if ANY file inside backend changes

'frontend/**'
→ triggers if ANY file inside frontend changes

'.github/workflows/deploy-app.yml'
→ triggers if the workflow file itself is modified

💡 Why this is important:

Without paths, even a small README change could trigger full deployment.

With paths, you optimize CI/CD so it runs only when needed.

🔁 2. pull_request block (runs on PR events)

pull_request:

👉 Meaning:

This triggers workflow when a Pull Request is created or updated.

👉 This is used for:

validation

testing

code quality checks before merging

📌 Branch restriction for PRs

branches:
      - main
      - qa
      - dev
Meaning:

This workflow runs only if the PR is targeting:

main
qa
dev

👉 Example:

PR → dev ✔ runs
PR → main ✔ runs
PR → some-feature-branch → ❌ may not run depending on target

📌 PR event types
    types: [opened, synchronize, reopened]

👉 types: defines what kind of PR activity triggers the workflow

Line-by-line:

opened
→ runs when a new pull request is created

synchronize
→ runs when new commits are pushed to the PR branch

reopened
→ runs when a previously closed PR is reopened

