What this block is

workflow_dispatch:
👉 Meaning:

This enables manual triggering of the workflow from GitHub UI or API.

Without this:

Workflow runs only on push, pull_request, etc.

With this:

You can click “Run workflow” button in GitHub and choose options.

👉 In short:

It adds a manual “deploy button” for your CI/CD pipeline.

🧩 Inputs section

inputs:
👉 Meaning:

This defines parameters you can pass when manually running the workflow.

👉 Think of it like:

“User input form for deployment”

🎯 Input: environment

environment:
👉 Meaning:

This is the name of the input variable.

You will later use it in workflow like:

${{ github.event.inputs.environment }}

👉 It tells the pipeline:

Which environment to deploy to (dev/qa/prod/etc.)

📝 Description

description: 'Deployment environment'
👉 Meaning:

This is just a UI label in GitHub Actions page

It helps users understand:

“What does this input mean?”

So when someone clicks “Run workflow”, they see:
👉 Deployment environment

❗ Required flag
required: true

👉 Meaning:

This means:

User MUST select or confirm a value before running workflow

If false → GitHub can use default automatically.

🟡 Default value
default: 'test'

👉 Meaning:
If user does NOT choose anything, GitHub will use:

👉 test
So pipeline will assume:

“Run in test environment”

🎛️ Input type
type: choice
👉 Meaning:

This restricts input to a dropdown selection in GitHub UI

Other types include:

string → free text input
boolean → true/false checkbox
number → numeric input
choice → dropdown menu (your case)

👉 So here user cannot type anything random.

📌 Allowed options
options:
  - dev
  - qa
  - test
  - prod
👉 Meaning:

These are the only valid values user can choose

So dropdown becomes:

dev
qa
test
prod
🔥 How it looks in real life

When you go to GitHub Actions → “Run workflow”, you will see:

👉 Environment (dropdown):

dev
qa
test
prod

Then you click:
✔ Run workflow

🚀 Why this is used in CI/CD pipelines

This block is used for:

1. Manual deployments
Deploy anytime without pushing code

2. Controlled releases
Choose environment manually (safe for prod)

3. Emergency fixes
Quick redeploy without new commit

4. Testing flexibility
Run same pipeline in dev/qa/prod

