# OIDC permissions for Azure authentication
permissions:
  id-token: write
  contents: read
  pull-requests: write
----------------------------------------


Simple mental model :

Permission	                Think of it as

id-token	                   “Can I login to cloud?”
contents	                   “Can I touch repo code?”
pull-requests	               “Can I interact with PR system?”



Meaning of each permission
1. id-token
👉 Purpose:

Used for OIDC (OpenID Connect) authentication

This is what allows GitHub to login to Azure without secrets.

🔹 id-token: write

Means:

GitHub can generate a secure token for cloud login (Azure/AWS/GCP)

✔ Required for:

Azure OIDC login (az login --federated-token)

GitHub → Azure authentication without secrets
🔹 id-token: read

Means:

Workflow can only read existing identity token, but NOT generate one

❌ Usually NOT enough for Azure login

⚠️ Impact:

Setting	Azure OIDC Login

write	✅ Works
read	❌ Fails


📦 2. contents

Controls access to your repository code

🔹 contents: read

Means:

Can clone repository
Can read files
Can build code

❌ Cannot:

push changes
commit back to repo

✔ Used for:

CI builds
Docker image creation
testing pipelines

🔹 contents: write

Means:

Can push commits
Can modify files in repo
Can tag releases

✔ Used for:

auto version bumping
release pipelines
CI that pushes build artifacts back

______________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________


💬 3. pull-requests

Controls interaction with PR system

🔹 pull-requests: read

Means:

Can read PR metadata
Cannot comment or modify PR
🔹 pull-requests: write

Means:

Can add comments to PR
Can update PR status checks
Can approve/label PRs (depending on token scope)

✔ Used for:

CI status updates
PR comments like “build succeeded”
automated review bots




